Kiess's founding anti-sealed-warrant doctrine was written with specific knowledge of the Black Ledger period — Evermeet's delta trade routes had participated in the same transfer system.
The obsidian disc bearing the Spirebound Conclave's triune seal held by the Syndic Council is Kiess-side documentation of the same chain the Black Ledger records from the delta end.
Kiess's formal position: all sealed Ash-and-Iron period records — Midgaard's trade ledger, Kowloon's Black Ledger, the Violet Compact's arcane-material registry — should open simultaneously under joint five-city commission review.
Simultaneous-opening prevents any single city bearing disproportionate reputational cost; Kiess calculated mutual exposure reduces each city's liability.
Kowloon and Midgaard Continuity factions declined; their Reckoning factions accepted in principle but lack authority.
Kiess's doctrine creates asymmetry: Kiess has repudiated sealed-warrant governance and loses less from opening records than cities that have not.

